	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Study concludes that new banana regime is likely to result in trade diversion</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A study has been published by ICTSD on ‘The implications for bananas of the recent trade agreements between the EU and Andean and Central American countries’. The analysis of the trade deal on bananas negotiated earlier this year by the European Union (EU) and eight Latin American states (Colombia, Peru, Costa Rica, El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala, Nicaragua and Panama) concludes that it is likely to result in a diversion of exports by Guatemala, Honduras, Nicaragua and, possibly, El Salvador from other markets to the EU, and an increase in production, exports and price received only for Peru, Costa Rica and Panama. Colombia is not expected to see any increase in exports to the EU although there will be a transfer of revenue from the EU (with a loss of tariff revenue) to elements in the banana supply chain. Ecuador (which has not signed the agreement) as well as the ACP and all other banana suppliers to the European market ‘are all expected to see their relative competitiveness on this market fall with respect to the signatories; <i>ceteris paribus </i>[other things being equal], they will export less to the EU and receive a lower price for their exports.’</p><p>These trade agreements, of which the provisions on bananas are considered among the key elements, are part of wider Association Agreements that also include cooperation and political dialogue. Before implementation, the European Council and the European Parliament as well as the partner legislatures must ratify the agreements. Ecuador ‘suspended’ its participation in the negotiations in 2009, although it has now declared an interest in resuming negotiations with the EU.</p><p>From the perspective of the ACP banana exporters, the key provision in the agreements is that the EU has agreed to progressively reduce its import tariff per tonne on bananas originating in these countries from €148 to €75 by 1 January 2020. The tariff would have reduced in stages to €114/t by 2020 in any case (under the changes already agreed by the EU to its MFN regime – for more information on the Geneva Agreement, see <i>Agritrade</i> articles ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/content/view/full/4860#74" target="_self">Banana deal struck</a>’, January 2010, and ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/content/view/full/4833#74" target="_self">Resolution of banana dispute pending</a>’, December 2009). But under the new regime, the signatories will benefit from a reduction in this standard rate that increases from 3 €/t in 2010 to 39 €/t from 2020. </p><p>A reason for the expected differential effect on exports from the eight signatory states is that there is a safeguard clause until 2020 under which the preferential tariff may be suspended for up to three months if imports from a specific country in a given calendar year exceed a ‘trigger import volume’ (TIV) for that year. The relationship of this country-specific TIV to recent and anticipated export capacity differs between each country. The study finds that the TIV for Colombia is much less generous than for the other signatories: it is no higher than the projected trend level of Colombia’s exports (so that any increase as a result of the agreement may trigger the safeguard clause). For the other signatories, the TIV is set at a level higher than the trend of exports in the recent past.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Giovanni Anania, ‘The implications for bananas of the recent trade agreements between the EU and Andean and Central American countries’, <i>Policy Brief, </i>No. 5, ICTSD, September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/publications/85064/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/publications/85064/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The impact of trade preferences like those just agreed with Latin America on the exports of the signatories (and the effect of this on other suppliers) is complicated to forecast, since it depends on what would have happened in the absence of the accord. The ICTSD study provides a helpful and very transparent assessment which shows the range of logical possibilities and the evidence for expecting one rather than another.</p><p>ACP and LDC exporters already have duty-free access to the European market, but their margin of preference over exports from the Andean and Central American signatory states will fall progressively over the implementation period. What effect this will have on the profitability (and hence volume) of their exports – compared with the ‘counterfactual’ of what would happen in the absence of the agreement – depends on whether or not it induces the signatories to increase their exports to the EU. </p><p>The TIV for Colombia appears from the ICTSD analysis likely to inhibit any major increase in the volume of exports, but for the other states there is scope to redirect some existing exports from other, less profitable markets to Europe. But this will depend partly on how the cut in EU tariff is passed on. If it accrues to producers or exporters in the signatory states it will make exporting to Europe more profitable. But if it is pocketed (in whole or in part) by EU-based traders, this will not necessarily happen. Forecasts have to make assumptions both about future supply capacity and on how the market works.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
